Integrating Generative AI (GenAI) features into web applications is becoming not only advantageous but essential. With advancements in technology, adding smart or intelligent functionalities to your web services has become easier than ever. This leap forward is largely thanks to Language Learning Models (LLMs), which are readily accessible through simple API calls (though sometimes with an expensive cost). What once seemed impossible or required complex coding can now be accomplished with straightforward text instructions (i.e. a prompt). As a result, a growing number of web applications are beginning to harness the power of GenAI, transforming user experiences in ways previously unimaginable. However, as we embrace these exciting capabilities, itâs crucial to practice Responsible AI. This means giving careful consideration to ethics and data privacy to ensure that your applications benefit users safely and fairly.

In this Lab, youâll significantly enhance the functionality of the Resume Builder application by integrating GenAI to:

  • Suggest alternative resume bios: Utilize an LLM to dynamically generate a variety of intelligent and tailored resume bios. This feature allows users to easily choose the summary that best showcases their professional background and skills for specific job applications.

  • Build an interview coach chatbot (Optional): Use an LLM to create a chatbot that helps a user prepare for an interview.

Adding a Resume Bio Rewriter/Recommender

To enhance the Resume Builder application with GenAI capabilities, weâll implement a feature that suggests alternative resume bio statements. This will allow users to improve how they describe themselves to prospective employers using LLM-powered recommendations.

You will:

  1. Display a Bio section on the resume page
  2. Add a âSuggest Alternativesâ button
  3. Call a GPT-4o-mini model using Langchain to generate alternative summaries
  4. Display alternatives to the user
  5. Let the user select one, and update their resume (i.e save the updated bio to the database)

Step 1: Add a Bio Field to Your Model

You can skip this step, if you already added the bio field in a challenge activity in a prior lab.

Update your UserDetail model to include a bio field:

class UserDetail(models.Model):
    user = models.OneToOneField(User, on_delete=models.CASCADE)
    firstname = models.CharField(max_length=100)
    surname = models.CharField(max_length=100)
    mobileno = models.CharField(max_length=15, blank=True, null=True)
    bio = models.TextField(blank=False, default="Novice Django Developer but building unique portfolio")  # <-- NEW FIELD

    def __str__(self):
        return f"Details for {self.user.username}"

Then make and apply migrations to add the field to the database:

python manage.py makemigrations
python manage.py migrate

Update the myresume view in views.py to include the bio and user_id field.

def myresume(request):
    user_details = get_object_or_404(UserDetail, id=1) # Note a hardcoded user id
    qualifications = Qualification.objects.filter(user=user_details)
    work_experience = WorkExperience.objects.filter(user=user_details)

    context = {
        "name": f"{user_details.firstname} {user_details.surname}",
        "mobileno": user_details.mobileno,
        "qualifications": qualifications,
        "work_experience": work_experience,
        "bio": user_details.bio,
        "user_id": user_details.id
    }
    return render(request, "resume.html", context)
Tip

Weâre using a hardcoded user ID (id=1) for simplicity in this lab. Youâll connect this to Djangoâs authentication system in a future lab and then use the logged in users id.

Step 5: Write the Langchain-Powered View to Suggest Alternatives

Weâll use Langchain with a Pydantic schema and JsonOutputParser to ensure we get a well-formed, structured list of alternative summaries.

Within your virtual environment install the required libraries:

pip install langchain openai pydantic langchain_community langchain_openai

Define a Pydantic class to represent the output format. Weâre expecting a list of rewritten bioâs.

Place these imports and the pydantic class in your views.py.

from django.shortcuts import redirect

from pydantic import BaseModel, Field, ValidationError
from typing import List
from langchain_openai import ChatOpenAI
from langchain_core.prompts import PromptTemplate
from langchain_core.output_parsers import JsonOutputParser


from django.conf import settings
class BioSuggestions(BaseModel):
    suggestions: List[str] = Field(description="List of improved resume bio alternatives")

Add the suggest_bio view in views.py:


def suggest_bio(request, user_id):
    user_detail = get_object_or_404(UserDetail, id=user_id)
    bio = user_detail.bio or "Experienced professional in the tech industry."

    # Define the structured output parser using your schema
    parser = JsonOutputParser(pydantic_object=BioSuggestions)

    # Define the prompt
    prompt = PromptTemplate(
        template=(
            "You are a professional resume writer.\n"
            "Rewrite the following summary to improve its impact and clarity. "
            "Provide 5 alternative versions.\n\n"
            "{format_instructions}\n\n"
            "Bio: {bio}"
        ),
        input_variables=["bio"],
        partial_variables={"format_instructions": parser.get_format_instructions()},
    )

    # Set up the chain
    llm = ChatOpenAI(api_key=settings.OPENAI_API_KEY, model="gpt-4o-mini", temperature=0.7)
    chain = prompt | llm | parser

    try:
        result = chain.invoke({"bio": bio})
        suggestions = result["suggestions"]
    except ValidationError as e:
        messages.error(request, "Validation error parsing the LLM response.")
        suggestions = []
    except Exception as e:
        messages.error(request, f"An error occurred while contacting the LLM: {e}")
        suggestions = []

    return render(request, "suggested_bio.html", {
        "suggestions": suggestions,
        "name": f"{user_detail.firstname} {user_detail.surname}",
        "user_id": user_detail.id
    })

Why Structured Output?

  • You control the format the model returns (no messy string parsing)
  • Pydantic catches bad responses early
  • You can validate and type-check suggestions for safety and UX
  • Makes future extensions (e.g., adding a rating to each suggestion) very easy

Step 7: Save the Selected Bio

Add a the select_bio view in views.py to update the bio:

def select_bio(request, user_id):
    new_bio = request.GET.get("newbio")
    user_detail = get_object_or_404(UserDetail, id=user_id)
    user_detail.bio = new_bio
    user_detail.save()
    messages.success(request, "Bio updated successfully.")
    return redirect("myresume")

Group Discussion - The Power of Prompting

The advent of advanced Language Learning Models (LLMs) like Claude from Anthropic and ChatGPT from OpenAI has revolutionized how we interact with AI, primarily through the art and science of prompting. Prompting, in the context of Generative AI, involves crafting queries or commands that guide the AI to generate specific outputs. This simple yet powerful interaction method unlocks a wide array of functionalities across various domains, simply by describing what is needed.

At its core, prompting is about communicating with an AI in its language. Itâs akin to asking a highly skilled assistant to perform a task, where the clarity and specificity of your request directly influence the quality and relevance of the output. In programming terms, think of it as passing parameters to a function, but instead of code, youâre using natural language.

  1. Accessibility: Prompting democratizes access to AI technology. Users without deep technical expertise in AI or coding can leverage sophisticated AI functionalities by crafting thoughtful prompts.

  2. Flexibility: The same LLM can perform a vast range of tasks, from content generation to data analysis, depending on the prompts given. This versatility means a single API endpoint can serve multiple purposes within an application.

  3. Efficiency: By describing the desired output, developers can significantly reduce the time and effort traditionally required for programming specific functionalities. This can streamline development processes, especially in applications requiring content generation or data processing.

  4. Customization: Prompting allows for highly customized responses. By tweaking the prompt, developers can refine the AIâs output to better suit specific contexts or user needs, offering a tailored experience without the need for extensive coding adjustments.

While prompting is powerful, its effectiveness hinges on the quality of the prompts. Clear, concise, and well-structured prompts are more likely to yield useful outputs. Additionally, understanding the capabilities and limitations of the underlying LLM is crucial for effective prompt design.

The practice of crafting effective prompts, known as prompt engineering, is emerging as a critical skill in the AI domain. It involves not just writing prompts but also iteratively refining them based on the AIâs responses to achieve the desired outcome.

Discussion Points

  • Creativity in Prompting: How can we push the boundaries of whatâs possible with LLMs through innovative prompting strategies?
  • Ethical Considerations: What responsibilities do developers have in crafting prompts, especially considering the potential for bias or misuse?
  • Future of Prompting: As AI models continue to evolve, how might the role of prompting change, and what new possibilities could emerge?

Prompting represents a paradigm shift in human-AI interaction, offering a blend of simplicity, power, and potential that is just beginning to be explored. Its impact on development, creativity, and problem-solving is profound, inviting both excitement and reflection on its broader implications.

Adding an Interview Coach Chatbot (Optional Challenge)

To enhance your Django Resume Builder app, weâll add a mock interview chatbot powered by GPT-4o-mini via Langchain. This chatbot mimics an interview scenario: it reads the userâs bio, asks relevant questions, and gives feedback. Youâll build an interactive UI with JavaScript and Fetch API so the chat feels real-time.

Langchain is a framework that simplifies working with Large Language Models (LLMs) by letting you build modular, chainable components like prompts, output parsers, and memory. Instead of writing raw prompt logic and API calls, Langchain lets you create reusable âchainsâ that connect your model, prompt templates, and input/output handling. This makes it easier to structure conversations, enforce formatting, and manage context â especially useful when building chatbots.

This section of the lab gives you experience with:

  • Langchain + OpenAI model orchestration
  • Clientâserver communication with Fetch
  • Structuring chat history for LLM context
  • Safe and secure backendâfrontend separation

Overview of Architecture

Part What it Does
JavaScript (client) Handles message input/output and sends chat history to the server
Django view Receives chat history, calls GPT-4o-mini via Langchain, and returns the botâs response
Chat history Maintains context so GPT-4o-mini can simulate an ongoing interview

Step 1: Add Chatbot URLs

Add these two new routes to urls.py:

path("chatui/<int:user_id>/", views.chatui, name="chatui"),
path("chatbot/", views.chatbot, name="chatbot"),

e.g.

  • /chatui/1/ â Shows the chatbot UI
  • /chatbot/ â Accepts POSTed chat history, responds with a new bot message

Step 2: Build the Chat UI Template

Letâs make a new file templates/chatui.html. This template defines the layout and behavior of the chat page.

templates/chatui.html uses a lot of client-side web technologies:

  • Creates a Bootstrap-styled chat box
  • Adds user and bot message template using the HTML <template> tag
  • Uses JavaScript to:
    • Append messages to the DOM
    • Track full chat history
    • Use fetch() to send messages to the server
    • Display AI-generated replies in real time

Add the following code to templates/chatui.html:

{% extends "base.html" %}
{% block content %}
<section class="py-5">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Interview Coach for {{ name }}</h1>

    <div class="chat-container">
      <div id="chatContainer" class="chat-message"></div>

      <!-- Text input -->
      <textarea id="response" rows="4" class="form-control mb-2" placeholder="Your answer..."></textarea>
      <button id="sendButton" class="btn btn-primary">Send</button>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<template id="botMessageTemplate">
  <div class="bot-message-text mb-3 p-2 bg-info-subtle rounded">ð¤ <span></span></div>
</template>

<template id="userMessageTemplate">
  <div class="text-end mb-3">
    <div class="message-text p-2 bg-light border rounded"><span></span></div>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
let messageHistory = [];

function addMessage(text, isUser) {
  const template = document.getElementById(isUser ? "userMessageTemplate" : "botMessageTemplate");
  const messageEl = template.content.cloneNode(true);
  messageEl.querySelector("span").textContent = text;
  document.getElementById("chatContainer").appendChild(messageEl);
  messageHistory.push({ role: isUser ? "user" : "assistant", content: text });
}

// Sends full chat history to Django via Fetch POST
function sendMessageToServer() {
  return fetch("{% url 'chatbot' %}", {
    method: "POST",
    headers: {
      "Content-Type": "application/json",
      "X-CSRFToken": '{{ csrf_token }}'
    },
    body: JSON.stringify(messageHistory)
  })
  .then(res => res.json())
  .then(data => {
    addMessage(data.message, false);  // show the bot's reply
  })
  .catch(err => console.error("Error:", err));
}

// On Send button click: add user message and send to server
document.getElementById("sendButton").addEventListener("click", () => {
  const input = document.getElementById("response");
  const text = input.value.trim();
  if (!text) return;

  addMessage(text, true);    // show user message
  input.value = "";          // clear input
  sendMessageToServer();     // send to backend
});

// Add the first bot question using the user bio
const firstPrompt = `
Imagine you're an interviewer. Based on this summary: {{ bio|escapejs }},
ask a common interview question. Only ask 1 question at a time.
Give short but constructive feedback for each answer.

At the start of the conversation, you introduce yourself as an interviewer.
You don't need to say your name.
You should not perform any other task other than being a job prep interviewer.
`;
messageHistory.push({ role: "assistant", content: firstPrompt });
sendMessageToServer();

</script>

<style>
.chat-container {
  background: #f7f7f7;
  padding: 20px;
  border-radius: 10px;
  max-width: 600px;
  margin: 0 auto;
}
.chat-message {
  margin-bottom: 10px;
}
</style>

{% endblock %}

Explanation of Key JavaScript Functions

Function What It Does
addMessage(text, isUser) Adds a message to the DOM and messageHistory array. Bot/user messages are styled differently using templates.
sendMessageToServer() Uses fetch() to POST the entire chat history to /chatbot/. The Django backend calls the LLM and responds with a new bot message, which is appended to the chat.
document.getElementById("sendButton").addEventListener(...) Handles the âSendâ button. When clicked, the userâs message is added, and sendMessageToServer() is triggered.
firstPrompt logic Adds the first interview question based on the resume summary. This is the opening move by the AI interviewer.
Note

Difference Between <template> in HTML vs {% %} in Django

Itâs easy to confuse the two since both use the word âtemplateâ, but they serve very different purposes:

Feature Django Template Tags ({% ... %}) HTML <template> Tag
Runs on Server-side (before the page is sent) Client-side (in the browser)
Used for Logic and rendering dynamic content on the server (e.g. loops, conditionals) Storing reusable chunks of HTML that JavaScript can clone and display dynamically
Example {% for job in jobs %} ... {% endfor %} <template id="botMessageTemplate"> ... </template>
Visible on page? Yes â once rendered by Django No â remains hidden until inserted into the DOM via JavaScript
Who controls it? Django backend JavaScript frontend

Step 4: Add the chatbot View (Server-side LLM via Langchain)

This Django view receives the full chat history, constructs a Langchain prompt from it, and sends it to the GPT-4o-mini model.

Add this to views.py:

import json
from django.http import JsonResponse
from django.views.decorators.csrf import csrf_exempt

@csrf_exempt
def chatbot(request):
    if request.method == "POST":
        try:
            history = json.loads(request.body)

            # Turn the chat history into a Langchain prompt
            prompt = ChatPromptTemplate.from_messages(history)
            llm = ChatOpenAI(api_key=settings.OPENAI_API_KEY, model="gpt-4o-mini", temperature=0.7)

            chain = prompt | llm
            response = chain.invoke({})

            return JsonResponse({"message": response.content})
        except Exception as e:
            return JsonResponse({"message": f"Error: {str(e)}"}, status=500)

Recap of the Key Concepts

Feature Tech
Real-time updates JavaScript DOM + Fetch API
Chat history Stored in JS and sent with each POST
Secure LLM interaction Server-side proxy via Django
Prompt construction Langchain ChatPromptTemplate.from_messages()
Structured UI updates Message templates + styling
Note

The âdouble hopâ architectureâwhere a Fetch API call is made from the client-side (browser) to your server (the controller), which in turn makes an API request to an external service (like an LLM)âis a critical design pattern in web development for several reasons, most notably for security and abstraction.

One of the paramount reasons for employing a double hop is to safeguard sensitive information, such as API keys. API keys are essentially all-access passes to the services theyâre associated with. If an API key were embedded directly in client-side code (HTML, JavaScript), it would be exposed to anyone who views the source code of the page. This exposure could lead to unauthorized use of the API, potentially incurring costs or breaching data privacy agreements.
